Topic 6 - Prompting Frameworks
Submitted By: Aman Dekate
Introduction
Prompting frameworks provide a structured way to design clear, reusable, and effective prompts. They help define roles, context, tasks, constraints, and expected outcomes, resulting in more accurate and consistent AI responses.
Exercise 1 – RTICFA Framework
Prompt:
Role: You are an experienced content writer.
Task: Write an engaging introduction for a blog.
Input: A mobile productivity app that helps users manage daily tasks, reminders, and schedules.
Context: The introduction will appear on the company's official blog to introduce the app.
Format: Write one engaging paragraph of 120–150 words.
Audience: Beginners looking for an easy-to-use productivity app.
Exercise 2 – ERA Framework
Prompt:
Expectation: Generate a polite and professional follow-up email that thanks the client, summarizes the discussion, and outlines the next steps.
Role: You are a Business Relationship Manager.
Action: Write a follow-up email after a client meeting.
Exercise 3 – APEX Framework
Prompt:
Action: Write an Instagram post.
Purpose: Attract local customers to the grand opening of a new café.
Expectation: Use a friendly, promotional tone, keep it under 100 words, include relevant emojis, and finish with a call-to-action.
Exercise 4 – TASK Framework
Prompt:
Task: Respond to a customer complaint about delayed delivery.
Action: Apologize, explain the delay, and provide a resolution.
Context: The shipment was delayed due to unexpected weather conditions, and the customer is frustrated.
Exercise 5 – CARE Framework
Prompt:
Context: New employees are joining the company during onboarding.
Action: Explain the company leave policy in simple language.
Result: Ensure employees clearly understand the leave policy.
Example: Include one example showing how an employee can apply for annual leave.
Exercise 6 – RISE Framework
Prompt:
Role: You are an experienced technical trainer.
Input: Explain the concept of APIs.
Steps: Explain what an API is, how it works, why it is useful, and where it is used.
Example: Include a simple real-world analogy such as ordering food in a restaurant.
Exercise 7 – CASE Framework
Prompt:
Context: A company is hiring fresh graduates for an entry-level software engineer role.
Action: Generate interview questions.
Scenario: Candidates have little or no professional experience.
Example: Include a mix of technical and behavioural interview questions.
Exercise 8 – ACRE Framework
Prompt:
Audience: Company employees.
Context: The organization will remain closed next Friday due to a public holiday.
Request: Draft a clear internal holiday announcement.
Example: Include a professional greeting, holiday details, and a closing wishing employees a pleasant break.
Key Learning
• Learned how structured frameworks improve prompt quality.
• Understood how different frameworks fit different use cases.
• Practiced designing complete prompts with clear roles, context, and expectations.
• Improved the ability to create reusable prompts for business scenarios.
Conclusion
Prompting frameworks make AI interactions more organized, consistent, and effective. Choosing the appropriate framework helps generate accurate responses for content creation, communication, customer support, technical explanations, and business workflows.

